<HEAD>Scandinavian Airlines Closes Continental Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian Airlines System</ORGANIZATION> completed a <MONEY>$50
million</MONEY> deal <DATE>Thursday</DATE> that makes it the largest shareholder of
<ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines Holdings Inc.</ORGANIZATION> and puts <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> out as
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> chairman.
   Lorenzo will get <MONEY>$30 million</MONEY> through the arrangement, approved a
day earlier by the <ORGANIZATION>Transportation Department</ORGANIZATION>, but a <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>
spokesman said the money is not all coming from the <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> purchase.
   ``<PERSON>Mr. Lorenzo</PERSON>'s <MONEY>$30 million</MONEY> is paid out over a period of time
through the company,'' spokesman Art <PERSON>Kent</PERSON> said. ``It's not like
he's getting a lump sum.''
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> said it paid Lorenzo <MONEY>$17 million</MONEY> to buy out his employment
contract and to obtain vested options he had in <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> stock,
although <LOCATION>Lorenzo</LOCATION> retains options on 783,333 shares. Lorenzo remains
as a <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> director.
   As part of the deal, <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> purchased <ORGANIZATION>Jet Capital Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, which
<PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> and partners used as a holding company for their shares of
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> also bought 2.25 million newly issued shares of
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> for <MONEY>$14</MONEY> per share.
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>, based in
<LOCATION>Stockholm</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Sweden</LOCATION>, issued a joint statement <DATE>Thursday</DATE> <TIME>evening</TIME> that
also announced several appointments to the 15-member <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>
board.
   As previously announced, the former president of <ORGANIZATION>Delta Airlines</ORGANIZATION>,
<PERSON>Hollis L. Harris</PERSON>, of <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION>, becomes president and chief executive
of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON>Harris</PERSON> also joins the board.
   Long-time <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON>Carl Pohlad</PERSON>, of <LOCATION>Minneapolis</LOCATION>, was
elected chairman. <PERSON>Robert Garrett</PERSON>, of <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, was elected chairman
of the executive committee.
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> said it would appoint three members to the <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>
board, including <PERSON>Jan Carlzon</PERSON>, of <LOCATION>Stockholm</LOCATION>, president and chief
executive of <ORGANIZATION>SAS Group</ORGANIZATION>. The other <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> appointees are <PERSON>Lars Bergvall</PERSON>,
of <LOCATION>Stockholm</LOCATION>, chief operating officer of <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>; and <PERSON>Roberto Mendoza</PERSON>,
of <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, vice chairman of <ORGANIZATION>J.P. Morgan</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
