<HEAD>Scandinavian Airline Reportedly Interested in Continental</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: SUBS 4th graf with 3 grafs from Texas Air spokesman; Picks up
5th pvs ``Texas Air ...''</UNK>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scandinavian Airline Systems and an unidentified
partner reportedly are involved in advanced talks with <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air
Corp.</ORGANIZATION> about buying all or part of the <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION> company's <ORGANIZATION>Continental
Airlines</ORGANIZATION> subsidiary.
   The parties have been discussing the form of a possible sale and
terms for some time, and now they have reached the point of trying
to draft a letter of intent, the Wall Street Journal reported today.
   Late last week, <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> said the company
may consider selling a minority or controlling interest in
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>. He said <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> officials had talked to interested
parties, but he gave no details.
   Art Kent, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>, said this morning he could
not confirm or deny the report.
   ``It's inappropriate to comment on anything like this,'' <PERSON>Kent</PERSON>
said.
   He said if discussions with an interested party ``reach a serious
point and a letter of intent is appropriate, there will be an
appropriate disclosure.''
   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest airline holding company, also
owns strikebound <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION>. The Miami-based carrier, which is
in the midst of bankruptcy reorganization, wouldn't be involved in
any transaction involving <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>, which currently has a 9.9 percent stake in <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> as part
of a marketing agreement, wouldn't be able to buy <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>
outright because of <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Transportation Department</ORGANIZATION> rules that
prevent foreign companies from having more than a <PERCENT>25 percent</PERCENT> share
in a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> carrier.
   Talks between the parties are an outgrowth of meetings that began
between <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> officials in <DATE>June 1988</DATE>, when the two
began work on the joint marketing agreement. Those talks turned to
<ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> possibly buying a stake in <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, and that aspect has been
pursued with new seriousness in the past 30 days, an unidentified
source told the Journal.
   The talks apparently heated up because of signs that
Houston-based <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> could remain profitable after massive
losses in <DATE>1987</DATE> and <DATE>1988</DATE> and the soaring value of airline stocks.
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> is <PERCENT>50 percent</PERCENT> owned by the governments of <LOCATION>Sweden</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Denmark</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Norway</LOCATION>. In <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>, its hub is <LOCATION>Copenhagen</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
