<HEAD>SAS Reportedly Interested in Buying Continental</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 10 grafs to UPDATE with analyst, union comment on possible
Continental sale.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, which is considering a sale of
part or all of its <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, reportedly is
involved in advanced talks about such a transaction with
<ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian Airlines System</ORGANIZATION> and an unidentified partner.
   Talks about the form of a possible sale and the terms have been
going on for some time, and the parties have reached the point of
trying to draft a letter of intent, the Wall Street Journal reported
in <DATE>Monday</DATE>'s editions.
   A <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> spokesman, however, would not confirm that any such
talks have taken place.
   ``I can't confirm or deny anything,'' spokesman Art Kent told <ORGANIZATION>The
Associated Press</ORGANIZATION>. ``It's inappropriate to comment on anything like
this.''
   Kent said if discussions with an interested party ``reach a
serious point and a letter of intent is appropriate, there will be
an appropriate disclosure.''
   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> announced last <DATE>Thursday</DATE> that the
Houston-based airline company _ the largest in the nation _ may
consider selling a minority or controlling interest in <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>.
<ORGANIZATION>Strikebound Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION> is <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>'s other airline
subsidiary, but it would not be involved in any <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>
transaction.
   Lorenzo said <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> officials have spoken to parties
interested in <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, but he has not provided any details about
the talks.
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> already has a <PERCENT>9.9 percent</PERCENT> stake in <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> as part of a
marketing agreement.
   If <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> is interested in buying part of Houston-based <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>,
the transaction would have to be structured in such a way that <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>
would get a minority holding. <ORGANIZATION>Department of Transportation</ORGANIZATION> rules
prevent foreign companies from having more than a <PERCENT>25 percent</PERCENT> stake
in a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> carrier.
   Talks that began in <DATE>June 1988</DATE> concerning the <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> marketing
agreement apparently turned to <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> possibly buying part of
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>. That aspect has been pursued with new seriousness in
the past 30 days, an unidentified source told the Journal.
   Signs that <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> could remain profitable after massive
losses in <DATE>1987</DATE> and <DATE>1988</DATE>, as well as the soaring value of airline
stocks, apparently heated up the discussions.
   Lorenzo's surprise announcement came a week after a <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION>
investment firm disclosed that it holds <PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>.
<ORGANIZATION>Loomis, Sayles &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION> portfolio management company, has
said its <PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT> stake was held for investment because it
believed <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> would show a profit in <DATE>1990</DATE>.
   The possible sale of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> could doom <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>, according to
securities analysts and labor leaders.
   Miami-based <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> is in the sixth month of a strike by
<ORGANIZATION>Machinists</ORGANIZATION> union members, pilots and flight attendants, and is
flying about a third of its pre-strike 1,100 daily flights.
   ``We've always believed that the plan was to shrink <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> and
roll it into <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON>Louis A. Marchesano</PERSON>, an analyst
with the <LOCATION>Philadelphia</LOCATION> brokerage <ORGANIZATION>Janney Montgomery Scott Inc</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``The sale of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> would mean <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> would have to make
it on its own,'' <PERSON>Marchesano</PERSON> said <DATE>Monday</DATE>, ``and the risk of a
shrunken <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> not making it is substantial.''
   Eastern, which filed for Chapter 11 protection from bankruptcy
shortly after the walkout began in <DATE>March</DATE>, is losing more than <MONEY>$1.5
million</MONEY> a day.
   The sale of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, according to <PERSON>Marchesano</PERSON>, would mean
Lorenzo ``might be leaving the airline business.''
   The <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION> spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION>Air Line Pilots Association</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Ron
Cole</PERSON>, agreed, saying that the <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> chairman ``may be cutting
and running.''
   A <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> without <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Cole</PERSON> said, would have only two
options _ continued liquidation of <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> assets or the outright
sale of the carrier.
   Striking <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> employees have repeatedly charged that <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON>
has been transferring <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> assets to <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, weakening
<ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> and strengthening <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``Now that the bankruptcy has thrown a net around <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s
assets and stopped the upstreaming of cash,'' <PERSON>Cole</PERSON> said, ``Lorenzo
has to admit that <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> can't go it alone, that it can't
survive without sponging off Eastern.''
</TEXT>
