<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / International Company News: Continental Air seeks extra
Dollars 3bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HOUSTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CONTINENTAL AIRLINES, one of the five largest <LOCATION>US</LOCATION> carriers, is seeking more
than Dollars 3bn in fresh equity and cash to restructure its debt-burdened
balance-sheet and help it out of bankruptcy in the next eight to 12 months.
<PERSON>Mr Hollis Harris</PERSON>, the new chairman of the airline which filed for protection
from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the US Bankruptcy Code last <DATE>December</DATE>,
said he was seeking the conversion of about Dollars 2bn of unsecured debt
into equity.
The airline currently has total unsecured debts of Dollars 2.5bn and secured
debts of Dollars 4.5bn.
<PERSON>Mr Harris</PERSON>, the former <ORGANIZATION>Delta Airlines</ORGANIZATION> president brought in to rescue
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, said it was planning to raise an additional Dollars 600m in new
equity from three or four investor groups.
The company has had discussions with business representatives at its three
<LOCATION>US</LOCATION> hubs of <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Denver</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Newark</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>New Jersey</LOCATION>.
At the same time, <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> is in advanced talks to sell a controlling
interest in its <LOCATION>Air Micronesia</LOCATION> operation in the <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION> for about Dollars
300m. But <PERSON>Mr Harris</PERSON> emphasised <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> would continue to be closely
involved in the operation in which it intended to retain a 49 per cent
interest.
The airline is also expecting to raise about Dollars 80m this year from the
sale of its Chelsea air catering company. It has already sold its <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION> to
<LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> route to <ORGANIZATION>American Airlines for Dollars</ORGANIZATION> 150m.
All these transactions coupled with the restructuring of the company
aircraft operating and capital leases are designed to reconstruct the
company's balance sheet and provide additional capital to expand the
airline.
<PERSON>Mr Harris</PERSON> stressed that <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> had to find a way not to shrink its
operations. The airline has 350 aircraft in its fleet and has 190 new <ORGANIZATION>Boeing</ORGANIZATION>
and <ORGANIZATION>Airbus</ORGANIZATION> jets on order.
'We must grow the airline as we come out of Chapter 11 (protection). We
cannot cut back. We have to grow and maintain market share if we are to
compete with the other big carriers,' he said.
But he acknowledged that the financial restructuring if successful was
likely to dilute significantly current shareholders' equity. This would
include <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian Airlines System</ORGANIZATION> (SAS) which currently owns 16.8 per
cent of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> shares and 18.3 per cent of voting rights.
'Their holding will automatically be reduced significantly under the
restructuring,' <PERSON>Mr Harris</PERSON> said. But he added that he expected <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> to invest
additional funds in <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>. 'We have a good relationship and I believe
they want to be a partner with us,' <PERSON>Mr Harris</PERSON> said.
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> reported this week a sizeable <DATE>first-quarter</DATE> loss of Dollars
194.8m compared with a Dollars 21.3m profit in the same quarter last year.
</TEXT>
