<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are key events in the evolution of <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines
Holdings Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, formerly known as <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, which filed for
protection from creditors <DATE>Monday</DATE> under Chapter 11 of federal
bankruptcy laws.
   <DATE>1934</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Varney Speed</ORGANIZATION> lines is formed in <LOCATION>El Paso</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>, with four
<ORGANIZATION>Lockheed Vega</ORGANIZATION> aircraft flying round trips to <LOCATION>Denver</LOCATION>. Earnings in
the first two weeks total <MONEY>$261.69</MONEY> from nine paying customers.
   <DATE>1937</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Varney</ORGANIZATION> is renamed <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION>. Its eight
employees relocate to <LOCATION>Denver</LOCATION>.
   <DATE>1968</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> opens routes to the <LOCATION>South Pacific</LOCATION>.
   1972 - Airline entrepreneur <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON>, future boss of
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, acquires <ORGANIZATION>Texas International Airlines</ORGANIZATION>.
   <DATE>1976</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Texas International</ORGANIZATION> offers ``Peanut Fares,'' the
precursor to the discount fares that would spread throughout the
industry after deregulation in <DATE>1978</DATE>.
   <DATE>1980</DATE> - <LOCATION>Lorenzo</LOCATION> creates <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, parent of <ORGANIZATION>Texas
International</ORGANIZATION>, headquartered in <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>.
   <DATE>1981</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> gains control of <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION>.
   <DATE>1983</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> employees strike, accusing Lorenzo of unfair
tactics to drive down costs. The airline, losing <MONEY>$1 million</MONEY> a day,
files for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal
bankruptcy laws. Employment drops from more than 12,000 a year
earlier to 4,000.
   <DATE>1984</DATE> - Using nonstrikers and new hires, <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> resurrects
much of its pre-strike operations. Lorenzo builds reputation as
anti-union manager.
   <DATE>1985</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> begins first European service. Lorenzo loses
a bid to buy <ORGANIZATION>Trans World Airlines</ORGANIZATION> as its employees, fearing his
union hostility, support takeover by investor <PERSON>Carl Icahn</PERSON>.
   <DATE>1986</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> re-emerges from bankruptcy with a plan to
fully repay all debts. Employment reaches 14,500 and aircraft fleet
totals 200, double the pre-bankruptcy level. Parent <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>
acquires <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION> as well as remnants of <ORGANIZATION>People Express</ORGANIZATION> and
<ORGANIZATION>Frontier</ORGANIZATION>, making it the largest airline operator in the country
with <PERCENT>20 percent</PERCENT> of the market.
   <DATE>1987</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s employment reaches 24,500 and fleet totals
more than 300 jets serving 140 destinations. Lorenzo introduces
``Maxsaver'' discount fares and announces plans to cut labor costs
at <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>.
   <DATE>1988</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> undertakes joint venture with <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian
Airline System</ORGANIZATION>, the beginning of a growing relationship between the
two companies. <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> also shows the effects of fare-cutting and
debt-financed spending spree, losing <MONEY>$466.2 million</MONEY> in <DATE>1987</DATE> vs.
earnings of <MONEY>$72.7 million</MONEY> a year earlier.
   <DATE>1989</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Lorenzo</ORGANIZATION> rejects <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> union demands in contract
negotiations, workers strike, <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> puts <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> under
bankruptcy-court protection and begins to sell many of its assets.
Parent company loses <MONEY>$885.6 million</MONEY> for the year, an industry
record. Lorenzo insists he'll remain in the airline business
despite speculation he might get out.
   <DATE>January-February 1990</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> drastically reduces proposal
for repaying <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> creditors and faces increased trouble in
bankruptcy court.
   <DATE>April 1990</DATE> - <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> loses control of <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> to court-appointed
trustee. <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> is renamed <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines Holdings Inc</ORGANIZATION>.
   <DATE>August 1990</DATE> - <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> resigns as chairman and chief executive
and sells most of his <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> holdings to <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian Airlines
System</ORGANIZATION>. He remains a board member.
   <DATE>November 1990</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> denies speculation it will file for
bankruptcy but concedes the board considered the move. Airline puts
some prized routes up for sale to raise cash. Lorenzo predicts that
trouble in the airline industry could leave just three or four
carriers dominating within a few years.
   <DATE>Dec. 3, 1990</DATE> - <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> files for protection from creditors
under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws, blaming the move on
excessive debt and high fuel costs.
</TEXT>
