<HEAD>Lorenzo Trying to Persuade Trump to Buy Continental</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air Corp</ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> has met
with <PERSON>Donald J. Trump</PERSON> in an effort to persuade the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> developer
to buy <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION>Trump</ORGANIZATION> associate said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
   ``<PERSON>Mr. Lorenzo</PERSON> and <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> have spoken,'' said <PERSON>Bruce Nobles</PERSON>,
president of <ORGANIZATION>Trump Shuttle</ORGANIZATION>, which the developer purchased from
<LOCATION>Lorenzo</LOCATION> <DATE>last June</DATE> for <MONEY>$365 million</MONEY>.
   But <PERSON>Trump</PERSON> has concerns about a potential purchase of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>,
a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Nobles</PERSON> said, noting that <ORGANIZATION>Trump</ORGANIZATION> is
concerned about <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s <MONEY>$2.5 billion</MONEY> debt, its small cash
reserves and the need to refurbish many of its planes.
   While <PERSON>Trump</PERSON> remains interested and believes his name would help
the Houston-based carrier win passengers, he has not been convinced
that the risks are acceptable, <PERSON>Nobles</PERSON> said in a telephone interview.
   ``His (<ORGANIZATION>Trump</ORGANIZATION>'s) concerns are well put,'' said <PERSON>Nobles</PERSON>, a former
<ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Pan Am Corp.</ORGANIZATION> official.
   Trump was unavailable for comment <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, a spokesman said.
Art Kent, a <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, said <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> had no
comment on the matter.
   In talks with <ORGANIZATION>Trump</ORGANIZATION>, said to have been held over the past month,
<PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> said his negative image has hurt <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, according to
sources quoted in <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>'s editions of the <ORGANIZATION>New York Times</ORGANIZATION>.
   Lorenzo announced last <DATE>Thursday</DATE> that Houston-based <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>, the
nation's largest airline company, may consider selling a minority or
controlling interest in <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Strikebound Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>'s other airline
subsidiary, apparently would not be involved in any <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>
transaction.
   Last week, <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION>The Associated Press</ORGANIZATION> that one reason he
was considering selling a stake in <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> was that the bitter
struggle with <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s unions had hurt traffic at <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> is also involved in talks about selling a major stake
in <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian Airlines System</ORGANIZATION> and an unidentified
partner, The Wall Street Journal reported <DATE>Monday</DATE>. <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> declined
to comment on the report.
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> already has a <PERCENT>9.9 percent</PERCENT> stake in <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> as part of a
joint marketing agreement.
   Sources were quoted by the Times as saying that <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> was
impressed with the way traffic on the former <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Air Shuttle</ORGANIZATION> in
the <LOCATION>Northeast</LOCATION> picked up since <ORGANIZATION>Trump</ORGANIZATION> bought it.
   Trump's share of the lucrative <ORGANIZATION>Northeast</ORGANIZATION> shuttle market, split
with <ORGANIZATION>Pan Am</ORGANIZATION>, has ``approximately doubled since we took over,''
<PERSON>Nobles</PERSON> said. Although he declined to give precise figures, he said
<ORGANIZATION>Trump Shuttle</ORGANIZATION>'s market share has jumped from around <PERCENT>25 percent</PERCENT> when
it started operations in <DATE>early June</DATE> to about <PERCENT>50 percent</PERCENT> currently.
   ``I think being separated from <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> is a positive; having the
<PERSON>Trump</PERSON> name is a positive; having better service is a positive,''
<PERSON>Nobles</PERSON> said.
   But rival <ORGANIZATION>Pan Am</ORGANIZATION> disputed <PERSON>Nobles</PERSON>' estimate of current market
share. <ORGANIZATION>Pan Am</ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON>Pamela Hanlon</PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION>Pan Am Shuttle</ORGANIZATION>'s
share, at around <PERCENT>75 percent</PERCENT> when <PERSON>Trump</PERSON> started up, is now holding at
roughly <PERCENT>60 percent</PERCENT>.
   ``We're quite pleased with the clientele that we think we've been
able to keep since they started,'' she said.
   The Times quoted its sources as saying that <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> favored a deal
with <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> involving <ORGANIZATION>Trump</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> board member <PERSON>Kaj Ikast</PERSON> said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> that the carrier was not
near a decision on taking a stake in <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>. Ikast told the
Times there have been talks with <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> about buying such a stake.
</TEXT>
