<HEAD>Report: Lawyers Prepared Chapter 11 Filing For Continental, Board
Split</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with report that company
considered Chapter 11, transition; PICKUP second graf pvs, The
board . . .</NOTE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE HOUSTON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of lawyers spent the weekend preparing a
Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing for <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, but the
carrier's board is split on how to deal with its financial
troubles, according to a published report.
   In its <DATE>early Wednesday</DATE> edition, The <ORGANIZATION>New York Times</ORGANIZATION> quotes an
attorney, who spoke on condition of anonymity, as saying the papers
were ready to be filed in bankruptcy court <DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>morning</TIME>.
   The airline denied the report.
   ``The company has no intention of filing for bankruptcy
protection,'' said <PERSON>Art Kent</PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> suffered losses during the normally busy <DATE>summer</DATE>
travel season and has been hurt by higher fuel prices since the
Iraqi invasion of <LOCATION>Kuwait</LOCATION>, the newspaper said.
   <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON>, who recently stepped down as chairman of
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> but remains on the board, opposes a Chapter 11 filing
by the airline, the <ORGANIZATION>Times</ORGANIZATION> said. Also, <PERSON>Jan Carlzon</PERSON>, chairman of
<ORGANIZATION>Scandavian Airlines System</ORGANIZATION>, which owns <PERCENT>16.8 percent</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>
stock, opposes filing for bankruptcy, the newspaper quoted the
lawyer as saying.
   A filing would reduce the value of <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>'s holdings.
   The newspaper said it was not clear which board members support
filing for bankruptcy protection.
   On <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> said it has moved to cut costs by
restructuring its senior management team, cutting five top
executives.
   The board of directors for the Houston-based airline approved
the restructuring plan on <DATE>Monday</DATE>.
   ``With radically higher fuel costs, <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> must become a
stronger competitor in the global marketplace,'' said <PERSON>Hollis
Harris</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive officer. ``We
have reaffirmed our intention to become a preferred airline among
frequent travelers around the world.''
   <PERSON>Harris</PERSON> was given the additional role of president, replacing
<PERSON>Mickey Foret</PERSON>, who is leaving the company to pursue other interests,
officials said.
   Also leaving the carrier will be <PERSON>Neal Neehan</PERSON>, senior vice
president-customer services; <PERSON>Clark Omstad</PERSON>, senior vice
president-properties and government affairs; <PERSON>Jim Arpey</PERSON>, senior vice
president-aircraft programs; and <PERSON>Elliott Seiden</PERSON>, vice president and
associate general counsel for <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines Holdings, Inc</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> named <PERSON>Thomas Kalil</PERSON> senior vice president-customer
service and announced <PERSON>Lewis Jordan</PERSON>, executive vice president and
system general manager, was given the additional responsibility for
managing the company's international division.
   ``These actions position <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> with a lean and efficient
management structure that reflects the realities of operating
during this fuel crisis,'' <PERSON>Harris</PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
