<LP>
   WILMINGTON, Del. -- A bankruptcy judge ruled that the
unsecured creditors of Continental Airlines Holdings Inc. can
sue former Chairman Frank Lorenzo and another executive to
recover money they received for selling their shares four
months before the company's bankruptcy-law filing in late
1990.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Helen S. Balick's action wasn't a
ruling on the merits of the case, merely the green light
necessary under bankruptcy court rules to proceed with it.
The action stems from Scandinavian Airlines System's purchase
of Continental shares owned by Mr. Lorenzo and Robert
Snedeker, another director.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The creditors claim the transaction deprived <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>
of an opportunity to sell equity to <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> at a time when the
company needed additional equity. In addition, they claim
that Messrs. <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> and <PERSON>Snedeker</PERSON> knew, or should have known,
that <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> was technically insolvent when it paid them
about <MONEY>$20 million</MONEY> to buy out their employment contracts.
   The creditors are seeking <MONEY>$180 million</MONEY> in compensatory and
punitive damages from the two men and <ORGANIZATION>Jet Capital Corp.</ORGANIZATION>,
through which they held most of their stake. <PERSON>Mr. Lorenzo</PERSON> said
the transactions were "appropriate and in the best interests
of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>."
   <PERSON>Judge Balick</PERSON> also allowed the creditors to seek recovery
of <MONEY>$124 million</MONEY> from the <ORGANIZATION>federal Pension Benefit Guaranty
Corp</ORGANIZATION>. The agency has said it will oppose the creditors'
motion.
</TEXT>
