<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 91 / International Company News: Continental brushes up its image
 -The airline's moves towards regaining financial health
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A jet in the new <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION> white, blue and gold livery was parked
in the humid sunshine at one of the gates of <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>'s new international
airport terminal last week.
It was one of the first 12 airliners to be repainted in the Houston-based
carrier's new colours.
Over the next three years, the entire fleet of 350 aircraft will be
repainted and refurbished as part of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to renew its
image and return to financial health.
'We know we are not out of the woods yet, ' said <PERSON>Mr Hollis Harris</PERSON>, the
former <ORGANIZATION>Delta Airlines</ORGANIZATION> president who replaced <PERSON>Mr Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> as chairman of
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> last <DATE>September</DATE>.
'It's not going to be easy, but I believe this country needs four or five
major carriers in the market place. I believe we will be one of those,' he
told journalists flown in from around the world to see <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s new
corporate identity.
Since <DATE>December</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> has been operating under Chapter 11 of the <LOCATION>US</LOCATION>
bankruptcy code.
It sought protection from its creditors to enable it to restructure its
heavily indebted balance sheet. It is now in the midst of a complex
financial restructuring exercise.
<PERSON>Mr Harris</PERSON> hopes it will enable the airline, the fifth largest carrier in the
<LOCATION>US</LOCATION>, to fly out of bankruptcy in the next eight to 12 months.
Many <LOCATION>US</LOCATION> airline analysts believe <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> has a reasonable chance of
pulling through, although much will depend on the length and depth of the <LOCATION>US</LOCATION>
recession, the speed and vigour of the recovery in air travel and the
success of the company's financial restructuring.
<PERSON>Mr Harris</PERSON> said when he landed at <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> he was impressed by the
airline's route structure, its staff and its overall potential. 'But the
financial situation was worse than I thought', he explained.
His original plan was to avoid filing for Chapter 11. He felt this would be
bad for staff morale since <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> had already been through a Chapter 11
bankruptcy in <DATE>1983</DATE> under <PERSON>Mr Lorenzo</PERSON>.
Instead, he put several <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> assets up for sale and his former
airline, <ORGANIZATION>Delta</ORGANIZATION>, showed interest in buying <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s extensive <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION>
operations. But with the economy weakening, rising fuel prices and the
impact of the <LOCATION>Gulf</LOCATION> conflict, <ORGANIZATION>Delta</ORGANIZATION> decided not to go ahead with a
substantial offer for the <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION> routes.
High fuel prices were also putting pressure on <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>. By <DATE>December</DATE>, <PERSON>Mr
Harris</PERSON> said, the company decided there was no alternative but to file for
Chapter 11.
However, <PERSON>Mr Harris</PERSON> adopted a radically different approach to the company's
previous Chapter 11 filing. Instead of launching a sweeping programme of job
cuts and internal restructurings, he adopted a 'business as usual' strategy.
The airline would continue to operate normally, while restructuring its
balance sheet. 'The plan was first to make the airline profitable and then
work to bring in additional capital to expand the airline,' <PERSON>Mr Harris</PERSON> said.
This month <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> reported a deeper <DATE>first-quarter</DATE> loss of Dollars 195m.
against a profit of Dollars 21m in the <DATE>first quarter of last year</DATE>. But <PERSON>Mr
Harris</PERSON> maintained the company had operated well since the filing, and with
traffic picking up again, he expected the airline to be operating in the
black in <DATE>July</DATE>.
But the financial restructuring poses a considerable challenge. The plan is
to convert about Dollars 2bn of unsecured debt into equity to reduce the
overall debt burden, including Dollars 2.5bn of unsecured debt and Dollars
4.5bn of secured debt. <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> is also restructuring its aircraft
operating and capital leases while painting and refurbishing the fleet.
To strengthen further the company's finances, <PERSON>Mr Harris</PERSON> is seeking to raise
an additional Dollars 600m in fresh equity. A further Dollars 150m will be
raised from the sale to <ORGANIZATION>American Airlines of Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>
route, and the company expects to sell its <ORGANIZATION>Chelsea</ORGANIZATION> aircraft catering
subsidiary for about Dollars 80m.
It is also planning to sell a 51 per cent stake in its <LOCATION>Air Micronesia</LOCATION>
operations in the <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION> which is expected to raise Dollars 300m.
a big impact on existing shareholders equity. <PERSON>Mr Harris</PERSON> said all present
shareholders would see their holdings greatly reduced. This would include
<ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian Airlines System</ORGANIZATION> which has a 16.8 per cent stake in the company
and 18.3 per cent of voting rights. But <PERSON>Mr Harris</PERSON> said he expected <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> to
invest additional funds in the <LOCATION>US</LOCATION> airline.
Apart from Seattle-Tokyo route and the <ORGANIZATION>Air Micronesia</ORGANIZATION> transaction,
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> does not intend to make any significant asset sales. Even in the
proposed <LOCATION>Air Micronesia</LOCATION> deal, <PERSON>Mr Harris</PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> would continue to
operate the service.
The airline already has plans to grow in the <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION> as well as in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>.
It already provides more services to <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION> than any other <LOCATION>US</LOCATION> carrier.
While the airline's biggest burden is its heavy debt, one of its biggest
strengths is its low cost base. This is why <PERSON>Mr Harris</PERSON> said he was committed
not to reduce salaries at <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>. 'Our people are the lowest paid in
the industry. Morale is high. That is helping us in bankruptcy', he
explained.
Although <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, unlike many airlines, does not have a cost problem, it
does have a revenue problem. At the end of the day, the success or failure
of its recovery strategy will depend on its ability to improve the quality
and yields of its revenues.
</TEXT>
