<HEAD>Shareholders Sue Continental Over Bankruptcy Filing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT spelling of Pohlad</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION> officials made misleading
comments about the troubled carrier's plans to seek bankruptcy
protection in an effort to prop up its stock value, according to a
lawsuit filed <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   Former chairman <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> and others artificially inflated
the market price of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> stock by denying in interviews with
the news media that the nation's fifth-largest airline was
considering filing for bankruptcy protection, according to the
lawsuit filed on behalf of shareholders.
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> disputed the allegations.
   ``As far as this airline is concerned, that suit is utterly
without merit,'' spokesman Art <PERSON>Kent</PERSON> said from <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>. ``In no way
were our shareholders or the public misled by any statements that
were made. At the time those statements were made, we had no intent
to file for protection under Chapter 11.''
   Continental filed for Chapter 11 protection from creditors on
<DATE>Monday</DATE>, saying it was forced into bankruptcy court by soaring fuel
costs and mounting interest payments on its <MONEY>$6.2 billion</MONEY> debt.
   The shareholders lawsuit, a class action filed in <ORGANIZATION>U.S. District
Court</ORGANIZATION>, was brought on behalf of investors who purchased <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>
stock between <DATE>Oct. 24</DATE> and the airline's bankruptcy filing.
   The shareholders said that during this time period, airline
officials publicly denied their intention to seek bankruptcy
protection even though ``such action was continually under
consideration as a solution to <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s worsening liquidity
and other financial problems.''
   The lawsuit accuses the airline officials of violating
securities laws and seeks unspecified damages because of losses on
investments.
   According to the lawsuit, <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> stock fell from <MONEY>$3.62</MONEY>{ per
share to <MONEY>$2</MONEY> per share after the bankruptcy filing.
   In addition to <LOCATION>Lorenzo</LOCATION>, the lawsuit names <PERSON>Jan Carlzon</PERSON>, chairman
of <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian Airlines System</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s largest shareholder;
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON>Carl R. Pohlad</PERSON>; and <PERSON>Hollis Harris</PERSON>, president
and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
