<HEAD>Became Known As Anti-Union During Stormy Career</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> parlayed his airline holding
company into a leading force in the industry, but along the way
incurred the wrath of organized labor which vilified him as a union
buster.
   The inability of Lorenzo and the unions to make peace with each
other played an indirect but important role in his announcement
<DATE>Thursday</DATE> that he was exiting the airline business after more than
two decades.
   The 50-year-old entrepreneur, who came to symbolize a tumultuous
decade of airline deregulation, said he is selling most of his
stake in <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines Holdings Inc.</ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian
Airlines System</ORGANIZATION>. The leading foreign carrier has held a small stake
in Houston-based <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> for two years.
   Lorenzo also is resigning as chairman and chief executive, to be
replaced by <ORGANIZATION>Delta Air Lines Inc</ORGANIZATION>. President <PERSON>Hollis L. Harris</PERSON>, a
highly respected manager lured to <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> after a discreet
search that started four months ago.
   The negative publicity that came to haunt <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> and his
company was an important element in his decision to get out,
<PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> told reporters at a news briefing in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>.
   ``It's been perfectly obvious to me that I personally have
become a lightning rod for many of the attacks that the company has
taken in the process of making the changes that have been
required,'' <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> said.
   ``This transaction allows me to step aside and allows the
company to have a new management,'' he said. Asked what he would do
now, <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> said, ``Take a little time to catch my breath. I
haven't had much time to do that.''
   The departure of Lorenzo marks the end of an era, but it didn't
end the criticism of him by organized labor.
   ``We can all shout `hallelujah!,''' said <PERSON>E.J. Breen</PERSON>, chairman of
the <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION> pilots strike committee.
   ``Clearly, nobody denies his genius to put deals together. But
as for his ability to operate (airlines), he's a complete
failure,'' <PERSON>Breen</PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION>, where
<ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> is headquartered. ``The way I'll remember him is as a
tyrant who destroyed lives and walked away with pockets full of
money and not a care in the world for what he has done.''
   Others reacted with a similar mix of satisfaction and
resentment. The <ORGANIZATION>International Association of Machinists</ORGANIZATION>, which has
led the <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> strike from the start, said he was largely
responsible for the problems in his company.
   ``<PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> demolished <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, wreaked havoc on
thousands of workers' lives and severely devalued <ORGANIZATION>Continental
Airlines</ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON>John Peterpaul</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>IAM</ORGANIZATION> general vice president. ``Our
condolences to whatever industry he stalks next.''
   Lorenzo will get nearly <MONEY>$30 million</MONEY> in severance payments and
sale proceeds. But that is only a fraction of what his airlines
were worth years ago in better times.
   From his plunge into the flying business in the <DATE>1960s</DATE>, the
<ORGANIZATION>Harvard MBA</ORGANIZATION> helped pioneer innovations ranging from cut-rate fares
to the industry's first hostile takeover. Lorenzo built his holding
company into the largest airline company in the country, owning
both <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>.
   In <DATE>1966</DATE>, he and <ORGANIZATION>Harvard</ORGANIZATION> classmate <PERSON>Robert Carney</PERSON> formed a
financial advisory firm. Two years later, they created <ORGANIZATION>Jet Capital
Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, which bought a controlling interest in <ORGANIZATION>Texas International
Airlines</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1972</DATE>.
   Lorenzo, then 32, was the carrier's youngest president.
   His image as a union buster began when he fought organized labor
at <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION> and won.
   In <DATE>1981</DATE>, <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> merged <ORGANIZATION>Texas International</ORGANIZATION> with <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>
after a bitter takeover battle. Two years later, he put
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, then the nation's eighth-largest carrier, under
bankruptcy protection, scrapped labor contracts and hired strike
replacements at lower pay.
   Lorenzo subsequently acquired <ORGANIZATION>New York Air</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>People Express</ORGANIZATION> and
Frontier airlines, which have been merged into <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>.
   He didn't face another labor fight until he acquired <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>.
The unions waged a bitter strike against the carrier and made
<PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> the target of their hatred.
   Lorenzo lost control of <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> altogether in <DATE>April</DATE> when <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
Bankruptcy <PERSON>Judge Burton Lifland</PERSON> placed the airline in the hands of
trustee <PERSON>Martin Shugrue</PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air Corp.</ORGANIZATION> then changed its name to
<ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines Holdings</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
