<HEAD>Lightning Rod Lorenzo Gone, But Company He Led Is Dogged By His
Legacy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Continental Airlines, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> is no longer boss at <ORGANIZATION>Continental
Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, but the carrier he shaped is following a road he traveled
in the early <DATE>1980s</DATE> when <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> first sought refuge under
federal bankruptcy laws.
   On <DATE>Monday</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines Holdings Inc.</ORGANIZATION> filed for
protection for a second time, blaming the move on the recent runup
in fuel costs and heavy debts accrued in the <DATE>1980s</DATE>.
   Lorenzo, the 50-year-old entrepreneur who came to symbolize a
tumultuous decade of airline deregulation, announced in <DATE>August</DATE> he
was selling off most of his stake in <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian
Airlines System</ORGANIZATION>.
   He also resigned as chairman and chief executive at <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>,
replaced by <PERSON>Hollis Harris</PERSON>, a respected manager lured from rival
<ORGANIZATION>Delta Air Lines Inc</ORGANIZATION>.
   Just <DATE>two weeks ago</DATE>, in his first public remarks since departing
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> warned that the troubles in the airline
industry could leave just three or four major airlines within three
years.
   ``And if you don't like air fares today ... just hold on to your
hats - you may not have seen anything yet in terms of air fare
price increases,'' he said.
   The predecessor to <ORGANIZATION>Continental Holdings</ORGANIZATION> was <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air Corp.</ORGANIZATION>,
which Lorenzo built into the nation's largest airline operator,
parenting <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION>. The growth of <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>
began in <DATE>1966</DATE> when <LOCATION>Lorenzo</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Harvard University</ORGANIZATION> classmate <PERSON>Robert
Carney</PERSON> formed a financial advisory firm.
   Even before that, in <DATE>1963</DATE>, <LOCATION>Lorenzo</LOCATION>'s first professional job was
in the industry, when he was hired by <ORGANIZATION>Trans World Airlines</ORGANIZATION> as a
financial analyst. Within two years, he was manager of the
financial analysis department at <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>.
   In <DATE>1968</DATE>, the Lorenzo-Carney duo created <ORGANIZATION>Jet Capital Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, which
bought a controlling interest in <ORGANIZATION>Texas International Airlines</ORGANIZATION> in
<DATE>1972</DATE>. Lorenzo, then 32, a <ORGANIZATION>Harvard MBA</ORGANIZATION> and son of Spanish immigrants
from <LOCATION>Queens</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.Y.</LOCATION>, was the carrier's youngest president.
   In <DATE>1981</DATE>, <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> merged <ORGANIZATION>Texas International</ORGANIZATION> with <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>
after a bitter takeover battle. His image as a union buster began
when he fought organized labor at <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> and won.
   The image grew in <DATE>1983</DATE> when he put <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, then the
nation's eighth-largest airline, under bankruptcy protection,
scrapped labor contracts and hired strike replacements at lower
pay.
   Lorenzo subsequently acquired <ORGANIZATION>New York Air</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>People Express</ORGANIZATION> and
<ORGANIZATION>Frontier</ORGANIZATION> airlines, which were merged into <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>.
   He didn't face another labor fight until he acquired <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> in
<DATE>1986</DATE>, where his relationship with unions was acrimonious and a
strike against the airline made him the target of union members'
hatred.
   Using <MONEY>billions of dollars</MONEY> in borrowed money and cheap fares,
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>, once high-cost airlines, helped <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>
become the nation's largest airline operator, capturing about <PERCENT>20
percent</PERCENT> of the domestic market.
   But with bitter resistance from the unions, particularly at
<ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>, both airlines came under extreme financial pressure and
there were doubts about <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s ability to survive.
   After the strike hamstrung <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1989</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> sought
bankruptcy court protection and is still operating under the
supervision of a court trustee who replaced <LOCATION>Lorenzo</LOCATION> in <DATE>April</DATE>.
   It was then that <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> began a quiet hunt for a new
leader, a search that resulted in the hiring of <PERSON>Harris</PERSON>.
   ``It's been perfectly obvious to me that I personally have
become a lightning rod for many of the attacks that the company has
taken,'' <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> said in announcing his departure.
</TEXT>
