<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEALS: MARKET WATCH; 
</P>
<P>
WHEN IT COMES TO AIRLINE BUYOUTS, NEITHER BORROWER NOR LENDER BE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN SLOAN, ALLAN SLOAN is a financial columnist for Newsday in New York. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Talk about good luck. A year ago, people at <ORGANIZATION>United Airlines</ORGANIZATION> were getting ready 
to slash their wrists because the <MONEY>$6.8-billion</MONEY> leveraged buyout of the company 
had fallen apart. Today, they ought to be sending thank-you notes to the 
Japanese bankers whose last-minute reluctance to lend blew the deal out of the 
sky. 
</P>
<P>
Because, you see, if the <MONEY>$300-a-share</MONEY> LBO had gone through, <ORGANIZATION>United</ORGANIZATION> would now be 
choking on a combination of high interest payments and Saddam Hussein-inspired 
fuel bills, the way that debt-ridden airlines such as <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Pan Am</ORGANIZATION>, 
<ORGANIZATION>USAir</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Northwest</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>TWA</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Midway</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Hawaiian Airlines</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>America West</LOCATION> are 
doing. 
</P>
<P>
Instead, <ORGANIZATION>United</ORGANIZATION>, like the country's two other major, relatively debt-free 
airlines -- American and <ORGANIZATION>Delta</ORGANIZATION> -- can stand the strain of higher fuel bills 
because its balance sheet is relatively debt-free. In fact, <ORGANIZATION>United</ORGANIZATION> has just 
ordered new airplanes and is in a dogfight with American for the right to buy 
choice European routes from debt-ridden <ORGANIZATION>Pan Am</ORGANIZATION>, which is once again selling 
prime assets in an attempt to keep itself afloat. 
</P>
<P>
The fact that <ORGANIZATION>United</ORGANIZATION> was lucky rather than smart is beside the point. If you 
compare the <ORGANIZATION>United</ORGANIZATION> that is to the United that would have been, you begin to see 
why, from the dawn of airline companies until junk bonds came briefly to rule 
the earth, loan officers were taught to be very careful about lending money to 
airlines. 
</P>
<P>
The reason, when you think about it, is obvious. Airlines can be very 
lucrative, but they're also very risky. There are expensive planes to buy, 
unpredictable fuel costs to meet, fickle customers to lure. As Chairman <PERSON>Herbert 
Kelleher</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Southwest Airlines</ORGANIZATION> said in an issue of Forbes magazine earlier this 
year, "You (can) go from spilling cash to bleeding red ink like the <LOCATION>Mississippi 
River</LOCATION> going through the <ORGANIZATION>Delta</ORGANIZATION>." 
</P>
<P>
Risks such as those are known as "operating leverage." Any time a company with 
operating leverage borrows a lot of money, it's piling financial leverage onto 
operating leverage. This doesn't merely add risk to risk; it multiplies them. 
It's the financial equivalent of mixing drinking and driving. 
</P>
<P>
But because shrewd and lucky financial operators such as <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Texas 
Air Corp.</ORGANIZATION> (now <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines Holdings</ORGANIZATION>) seemed to be the wave of the 
future, the old rule about not combining operating risk with financial risk 
went out the window. 
</P>
<P>
Any airline that wasn't loaded with debt was accused of not having done the 
right thing by its shareholders. Analysts snickered at <ORGANIZATION>Delta</ORGANIZATION> for not being 
daring enough. <PERSON>Marvin Davis</PERSON>, the <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> billionaire, raided <ORGANIZATION>United</ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON>Donald 
J. Trump</PERSON>, then a real estate mogul, now a deadbeat, was threatening to raid 
American. 
</P>
<P>
Who's laughing now? <ORGANIZATION>Northwest Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, which went private in a leveraged 
buyout that Chairman <PERSON>Alfred A. Checchi</PERSON> boasts is two years ahead of schedule in 
repaying its debt, is talking about "major layoffs." Hawaiian, another LBO, is 
on the brink of financial failure. <ORGANIZATION>TWA</ORGANIZATION>, hocked to the eyeballs by <PERSON>Carl C. Icahn</PERSON> 
to buy out its shareholders and make huge payments to him, is choking. <ORGANIZATION>Braniff</ORGANIZATION> 
has gone broke for the second time. <ORGANIZATION>USAir</ORGANIZATION>, which borrowed heavily to buy other 
companies, is being squeezed, as are Midway and <LOCATION>America West</LOCATION>. 
</P>
<P>
"We have proven that airlines are not candidates for LBOs," <ORGANIZATION>Pan Am</ORGANIZATION> Chairman 
<PERSON>Thomas G. Plaskett</PERSON> told a group of travel agents earlier this month. "They 
generate enough operating and financial leverage on their own, let alone adding 
to the leverage to provide payouts to shareholders." Indeed. 
</P>
<P>
Then there's our old friend <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines Holdings</ORGANIZATION>, formerly <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>. 
The news leaked last week that <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> had considered going Chapter 11 but 
decided not to do so. The disclosure that the company had thought of going 
Chapter 11 may well end up forcing it into Chapter 11 because suppliers will 
probably cut back on credit and travel agents may stop booking <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> 
flights. They remember getting burned in <DATE>1983</DATE>, when <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> put <ORGANIZATION>Continental 
Airlines</ORGANIZATION> into bankruptcy, and again in <DATE>1989</DATE>, when it was <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s turn to go 
belly up. 
</P>
<P>
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, which had <MONEY>$2.6 billion</MONEY> in debt and long-term leases on its books 
as of <DATE>June 30</DATE> -- not counting <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s multibillion-dollar debt -- said it is 
thinking of selling its foreign routes to help buy its way out of trouble. The 
problem is that <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> has pledged its foreign routes to the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Pension 
Benefit Guaranty Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, the federal agency that insures pensions. The agency 
got <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> to pledge those assets to guarantee payment of the shortfall in 
<ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s pension plan, a gap that the agency puts at <MONEY>$565 million</MONEY>. <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> 
is still on the hook for <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s pension plan, even though a bankruptcy judge 
took control of <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> away from <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> six months ago. 
</P>
<P>
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s press relations people, as usual, wouldn't take my call. I didn't 
even bother trying to find Lorenzo, whom I've called for more than 10 years but 
who has never called me back. 
</P>
<P>
But the Chapter 11 prospect makes <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON>'s departure from <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> this 
<DATE>August</DATE> look more than a little suspicious. Lorenzo, you recall, bailed out with 
<MONEY>$27 million</MONEY>, thanks to a deal he cut with <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian Airline Systems</ORGANIZATION> to sell 
his <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> stock and stock options for about triple the market price. 
That's continuing the pattern in which Lorenzo cut special deals with the 
company that put <MONEY>millions of dollars</MONEY> in his pocket at the expense of other 
shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
Poor Frank. He said in <DATE>August</DATE> that he was leaving <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> to let <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> run it 
unhindered. Yeah, right. At least when the Titanic sank, the captain had enough 
class to go down with the ship. 
</P>
<P>
Oops Department: <DATE>Last week</DATE>, in my <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION> Celtics column, I wrote that master 
limited partnerships will lose their tax breaks after <DATE>1997</DATE>. I should have said 
"most MLPs," because the post-1997 rule doesn't apply to real estate and 
natural resource MLPs. 
</P></TEXT>
