<HEAD>Scandinavian Airline Makes Deal With U.S. Carrier</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New York news conference scheduled to begin 8 a.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian Airlines System</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air Corp.</ORGANIZATION> scheduled a
joint <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> <TIME>morning</TIME> news conference in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> to announce what
<ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> said was a major cooperation deal with a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> airline.
   The news conference comes amid unconfirmed reports in the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> that <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> might acquire a stake in <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>, or
that the two companies would engage in a cooperative business
effort.
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> scheduled an <TIME>8 a.m. EDT</TIME> news conference at <LOCATION>New
York</LOCATION>'s Plaza Hotel to announce the deal. <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON>Frank
Lorenzo</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON>Jan Carlzon</PERSON> also scheduled a later news
conference at the Plaza.
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION>Stockholm</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Sweden</LOCATION> said <DATE>Monday</DATE> the airline had
reached a cooperation deal with a major <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> carrier, but declined
to give details or identify the carrier.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Washington Post</ORGANIZATION> reported in its <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> editions that <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>
was negotiating to buy a stake in Houston-based <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>, the
owner of <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> airlines. Citing unidentified
industry sources, the newspaper said <PERSON>Carlzon</PERSON> traveled to <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> in
recent weeks to negotiate with the airline holding company.
   <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>'s <ORGANIZATION>New York Times</ORGANIZATION> indicated <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> were
expected to announce an agreement to coordinate their schedules to
offer customers the shortest times between major destinations, in
an attempt to attract more business travelers.
   Other reports speculated <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> would buy some of <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s
<LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> or domestic <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> routes, including landing rights in
<LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION>, to which <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> long has sought access.
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> information director <PERSON>Knut Lovstuhagen</PERSON> refused to confirm
reports on <DATE>Monday</DATE>, but said the deal was ``extensive.''
   The Scandinavian flag carrier, which is <PERCENT>50 percent</PERCENT> owned by the
governments of <LOCATION>Sweden</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Denmark</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Norway</LOCATION>, has tried to develop a
``global axis'' strategy.
   But negotiations on several other deals fell through last year,
including talks with the Belgian national carrier <ORGANIZATION>SABENA</ORGANIZATION>, with
British Caledonian and with <ORGANIZATION>Aerolinas Argentinas</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> is the largest <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> airline company, while <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> is the
eighth-largest European airline.
</TEXT>
