<HEAD>Analysts Believe Continental Can Still Fly Without Lorenzo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now that <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> is leaving <ORGANIZATION>Continental
Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, the question remains whether the carrier can rise above
the problems it accumulated on its way to the top.
   Lorenzo's departure may have stemmed the flow of harsh criticism
from organized labor, but the carrier still faces other obstacles.
   Heavy debts and a bitter strike at sister carrier <ORGANIZATION>Eastern
Airlines</ORGANIZATION> have hurt business, and <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> still suffers from an
image problem. But despite those hurdles, several analysts said
<DATE>Friday</DATE> there is room for optimism.
   ``It is a fairly low-cost provider. With a different kind of
management, it could be a very powerful airline,'' said industry
analyst <PERSON>Andrew Geller</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>PNC Financial Corp.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Philadelphia</LOCATION>.
   ``I think it definitely has a better future now, or a heightened
chance of a better future with this happening,'' <PERSON>Geller</PERSON> said.
``Whether I think it's a survivor, I don't know yet.''
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines Holdings Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, formerly known as <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air
Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, announced <DATE>Thursday</DATE> that <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> was selling most of his
stake in the company to <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian Airlines System</ORGANIZATION> and resigning
as chairman and chief executive.
   Lorenzo will be replaced by <ORGANIZATION>Delta Air Lines Inc</ORGANIZATION>. President
<PERSON>Hollis L. Harris</PERSON>.
   The Houston-based company once commanded <PERCENT>20 percent</PERCENT> of the
domestic airline market through its ownership of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> and
its sister carrier, Miami-based <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>.
   <PERSON>Robert J. Joedicke</PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION>Lehman Brothers</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said the
carrier has several advantages and disadvantages as it moves into
the post-Lorenzo era.
   ``Its labor costs are lower than the industry average. Whoever
takes it over is blessed with a low-cost airline,'' he said. ``They
can be quite competitive among the major carriers.''
   The company's debt, however, ``sort of counterbalances that,''
<PERSON>Joedicke</PERSON> said. Its success, he said, depends on whether management
can realign the structure of its debt, which totaled some <MONEY>$4.8
billion</MONEY> as of <DATE>March 31</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Joedicke</PERSON> also said he believes <PERSON>Harris</PERSON> will make strides in
improving service, which should help attract additional business
travelers.
   ``They kind of had a reputation of bad service that they were
slowly getting rid of, this may hasten that,'' said <PERSON>Thomas Canning</PERSON>
of <ORGANIZATION>Standard &amp; Poor</ORGANIZATION>'s in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>.
   Canning said <PERSON>Harris</PERSON> is well respected in the airline industry
and should be instrumental in polishing <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s tarnished
image.
   But <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> also faces problems common throughout the
airline industry, including high fuel costs, sagging traffic growth
and increased competition, he said.
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, he said, needs to attract a loyal following and
obtain a larger share of the flying public. He said that except for
<PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON>'s surprise departure, he doubted there would be any major
changes immediately.
</TEXT>
