<HEAD>Lorenzo Considering Sale of Stake in Continental</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS new 4th graf to ADD SAS stake in Texas Air; picks up
4th graf pvs bg'ng, Late Thursday, ...; ADDS 8 grafs at end to UPDATE with
analysts' comments; No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air Corp.</ORGANIZATION> says it is considering selling a
minority or controlling stake in its <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION> subsidiary
and has talked to parties interested in the airline.
   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest airline company, also said
<DATE>Thursday</DATE> it has hired an investment adviser to explore a possible
transaction.
   The announcement came a week after a <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION> investment firm
disclosed that it holds <PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>, which also owns
strike-plagued <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION>Loomis, Sayles &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION>
portfolio management company, has said its <PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT> stake was held
for investment because it believed <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> would show a profit in
<DATE>1990</DATE>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian Airlines System</ORGANIZATION> owns around <PERCENT>10 percent</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>.
   Late <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> released a statement saying its
chairman, <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON>, revealed that the company was considering a
possible sale of an interest in <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> during a management
conference.
   Lorenzo said in a statement there were arguments in favor of
selling <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, such as giving the airline access to stronger
financial resources.
   However, he said, ``there are also a number of compelling reasons
why a sale of the company may not be advisable.''
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> is emerging from a period of consolidations with
other airlines as a stronger company and shows potential for
improved financial results, <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> said.
   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> said it retained the investment firm <ORGANIZATION>Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.</ORGANIZATION> as an adviser on any transaction. <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> spokesman
<PERSON>Ned Walker</PERSON> declined to comment further on the statement.
   Miami-based <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> is in the midst of Chapter 11 bankruptcy
reorganization. The carrier filed for protection from its creditors
on <DATE>March 9</DATE>, five days after its machinists, pilots and flight
attendants went on strike. Since then, it has been rebuilding as a
smaller airline using non-union workers.
   In <DATE>1983</DATE>, <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> followed a similar path with <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>.
   Airline industry analysts expressed surprise at <LOCATION>Lorenzo</LOCATION>'s
announcement.
   ``I expected <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> would be the last thing he would dispose
of,'' said <PERSON>Louis Marckesano</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Janney Montgomery Scott Inc.</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Philadelphia</LOCATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> would carry a sale price of about <MONEY>$2 billion</MONEY> if it
were sold in its entirety, and <LOCATION>Lorenzo</LOCATION> may just be trying to find
out what <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> is worth, he suggested.
   ``He might just be testing the waters,'' <PERSON>Marckesano</PERSON> said.
   Many observers had expected <LOCATION>Lorenzo</LOCATION> to fold the remnants of
<ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> into <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, he noted.
   ``The worst may be over and it surprises me he would be
considering a major sale,'' said <PERSON>Daniel Hersh</PERSON>, an analyst with
<PERSON>Bateman Eichler</PERSON>, <PERSON>Hill Richards</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>.
   He speculated that Lorenzo might be considering bringing in a
high-profile purchaser to change <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s image as a low-fare
carrier that does not appeal to business travelers.
   ``I think the biggest problem is the image of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> with
the business travelers,'' <PERSON>Hersh</PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
