<HEAD>SAS, Texas Air Sign Cooperation Pact</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS new 4th graf to UPDATE with no comment from Texas Air;
picks up 4th graf pvs bg'ng, Some say ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new <MONEY>$50 million</MONEY> agreement between <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian
Airlines System</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air Corp.</ORGANIZATION> is designed to strengthen the
competitive positions of both companies, officials say.
   Separately, a report published <DATE>today</DATE> said <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> is holding
discussions to sell its <LOCATION>East Coast</LOCATION> air shuttle to developer <PERSON>Donald
Trump</PERSON>. According to unidentified sources quoted by The Wall Street
Journal, the pricetag on the three-city shuttle is in the <MONEY>$200
million</MONEY> range.
   As evidence the shuttle is up for sale, Journal sources noted
that planes and lounge areas have been refurbished, and attendants
are getting new uniforms. The service is run by <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> declined comment on the Journal report, said <PERSON>Mark
Johnson</PERSON>, a spokesman for the airline company. Representatives of
<LOCATION>Trump</LOCATION> weren't immediately available for comment.
   Some say <PERSON>Trump</PERSON> might use the shuttle, which operates between
<LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION>, to help draw people to his hotel
and casino properties in <LOCATION>Atlantic City</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.J.</LOCATION>
   <ORGANIZATION>Trump</ORGANIZATION> already operates a helicopter service between <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Atlantic City</LOCATION>.
   Under <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>'s agreement with <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>, the Scandinavian airline
will lease airport gates in the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> area and have the right to
buy up to <PERCENT>10 percent</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>'s stock on the open market.
   The accord, signed <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, also includes provisions for
coordinating marketing, reservations and scheduling, and the
companies will establish a joint training program for airline
workers.
   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>, the largest <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> airline company, owns <ORGANIZATION>Continental
Airlines</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, which have been hurt by financial
losses, labor problems and complaints about service.
   SAS, renowned for service but weak in scheduling connections to
the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, has been seeking ways of positioning itself to
exploit the era of European deregulation that will begin in <DATE>1992</DATE>.
   ``Our aim is to maximize efficiency and provide the best
professional service to business travelers anywhere in the world,''
<ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> told reporters at a <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> press
briefing.
   Under the agreement, <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> will pay <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> <MONEY>$15 million</MONEY> to
lease three gates at <LOCATION>Newark International Airport</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>New Jersey</LOCATION>,
beginning next <DATE>spring</DATE>. <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> will pay <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> <MONEY>$10 million</MONEY> for a
similar lease arrangement at <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>'s <LOCATION>John F. Kennedy
International Airport</LOCATION> in <DATE>1991</DATE>.
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> also will pay <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> <MONEY>$25 million</MONEY>.
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> will have the right to buy up to <PERCENT>10 percent</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>'s
stock on the open market, and <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> officials said they intended to
make the purchases within six months.
   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> stock was the most actively traded issue <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> on
the <ORGANIZATION>American Stock Exchange</ORGANIZATION>, declining 12<MONEY>{ cents</MONEY> to <MONEY>$14.25</MONEY>. The
company has 39.9 million shares outstanding.
   Jan <PERSON>Carlzon</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> president and chief executive officer, will
become a member of <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors.
   The marriage of a financially pressed <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> airline company and a
service-oriented European carrier makes sense for both, analysts
said.
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> will get the access to <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> routes that it is seeking while
<ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> will get cash that it needs, noted <PERSON>Anthony Hatch</PERSON>, an
analyst for <ORGANIZATION>Argus Research Corp</ORGANIZATION>.
   The agreement is not unprecedented, but it combines elements of
existing arrangements in a new way. <ORGANIZATION>United Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, the biggest
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> carrier, signed an agreement with <ORGANIZATION>British Airways</ORGANIZATION> late last
year setting up a worldwide marketing partnership.
   But unlike the accord between <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>, the
<ORGANIZATION>United-British Airways</ORGANIZATION> combination doesn't include an equity stake.
<ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>' equity stake in <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> ``helps them cement the alliance,''
<PERSON>Hatch</PERSON> said.
   As European deregulation approaches, similar accords between
major airlines in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> are likely to crop
up, said <PERSON>Andrew Geller</PERSON>, an airline analyst for <ORGANIZATION>Provident National
Bank</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Philadelphia</LOCATION>.
   In another case, <ORGANIZATION>Ansett Transport Industries Ltd.</ORGANIZATION>, an Australian
conglomerate owned 50-50 by media tycoon <ORGANIZATION>Rupert Murdoch</ORGANIZATION> and
transportation company <ORGANIZATION>TNT Ltd.</ORGANIZATION>, has a <PERCENT>20 percent</PERCENT> stake in <ORGANIZATION>America
West Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION>Tempe</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ariz</LOCATION>. The two do not have a
cooperative agreement.
   Officials of <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> said they began discussions for
such an alliance about nine months ago, at <LOCATION>Lorenzo</LOCATION>'s initiative.
<ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> has similar arrangements with <ORGANIZATION>Thai International Airways</ORGANIZATION> of
<LOCATION>Thailand</LOCATION>, and recently purchased a stake in <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s national
carrier.
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> currently has services from <LOCATION>Newark International
Airport</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION>, and from <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>. SAS, heavily
used by business travelers, flies between <LOCATION>Scandinavia</LOCATION> and four <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
cities: <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION>.
   The Scandinavian flag carrier, <PERCENT>50 percent</PERCENT> owned by the
governments of <LOCATION>Sweden</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Denmark</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Norway</LOCATION>, has tried to develop
what its management calls a ``global axis'' strategy to provide
travelers with the most convenient connections through a network of
cooperation pacts with other carriers.
</TEXT>
