<BYLINE>Lorenzo Says He's Not Quitting Business</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air Corp</ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> insists
that he plans to remain in the airline business, countering
speculation that he might quit.
   A defiant <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> also said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> that <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Eastern
Airlines</ORGANIZATION> subsidiary will start turning a profit next year, despite
the strikebound carrier's enormous debts and bankruptcy proceeding.
   While about 100 <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> strikers chanted anti-Lorenzo slogans
outside the long-delayed <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> annual meeting, the chairman of
the nation's biggest airline company told shareholders he has no
plans to quit the business, won't sell <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> and likely will have
<ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> assume some of <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s financial obligations.
   ``I have no intentions of leaving the airline business,'' <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON>
said at a news conference after the meeting. ``I plan to be around
for plenty of years to come, God willing.''
   Speculation that <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> might quit was fueled by his surprise
announcement <DATE>Aug. 24</DATE> that he was considering selling all or part of
Houston-based <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>'s other main
subsidiary. He had no comment on a statement <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> by <PERSON>Jan
Carlzon</PERSON>, managing director of <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian Airlines System</ORGANIZATION>, that <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>
has no ``immediate interest'' in buying part of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>, which owns a 9.9 percent stake in <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>, has been in
talks with <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> officials about possibly buying part of
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>. Under <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> law, foreign airlines are allowed to own up
to <PERCENT>25 percent</PERCENT> of an American carrier.
   Security was tight at the hotel where the shareholders meeting
took place, largely because of <LOCATION>Lorenzo</LOCATION>'s unpopularity among <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>
strikers. Stockholders had to pass through metal detectors,
television cameras were banned from the meeting room and <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>
uniformed and plainclothes police as well as private security guards
were present.
   Lorenzo's remarks about Miami-based <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> came as the airline
is mired in the seventh month of a strike that has become a national
symbol of labor resistance and has left thousands of pilots, flight
attendants and <ORGANIZATION>Machinists</ORGANIZATION> union members walking picket lines
demanding <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON>'s resignation.
   Eastern has been replacing the strikers with picket-line crossers
and non-union hires and is flying a limited operation, but it is
doing business under the protection of federal bankruptcy court _
where it sought protection from creditors five days after the strike
began <DATE>March 4</DATE>.
   If <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> were sold, some observers believe <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> might
liquidate <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> and quit the business.
   But the airline chief told about 300 shareholders at the meeting
that <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> ``is projecting profitable operations beginning next
year.'' The stockholders responded with applause.
   Eastern has made an ``astonishing rebound from the devastation
caused by the strike of its three unions, and is recovering much
faster than expected,'' <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> said during the hourlong meeting.
   He said <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s proposed reorganization plan, submitted to
bankruptcy court <DATE>July 21</DATE>, likely will receive final court approval
by year end or early next year, clearing the way for the airline to
emerge from bankruptcy at about two-thirds its pre-strike size.
   ``<ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> is standing behind <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, and the
possibility is excellent that <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> will assist <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>,'' said
<PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON>, who aggressively built the parent company from a small
intrastate carrier into an airline empire.
   The annual meeting coincided with a hearing in <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Bankruptcy
Court in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> at which a judge approved a plan for payment of
<MONEY>$98.3 million</MONEY> <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> owes to employee pension plans. <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> is
lending <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> <MONEY>$45 million</MONEY> toward the payment, <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> is paying
<MONEY>$27 million</MONEY> with the proceeds of asset sales, and the rest has been
deferred until <DATE>July 1990</DATE>.
   Eastern's proposed reorganization calls for repaying all
creditors in full, including refunding the price of tickets that
weren't used because of the walkout.
   The strikers have been pushing for a sale of <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> in its
entirety and have allied themselves in that effort with <PERSON>Joseph
Ritchie</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION> businessman. Eastern, meanwhile, has been selling
aircraft, routes and airport gates to raise money toward paying off
its <MONEY>$2.3 billion</MONEY> debt.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Air Line Pilots Association</ORGANIZATION>, which represents pilots at
nearly all the nation's major carriers, has spent <MONEY>$69.5 million</MONEY> _
about <PERCENT>57 percent</PERCENT> of its contingency fund _ on the battle with
<ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>. Pilots at the other airlines have provided strike benefits
to <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> pilots averaging about <MONEY>$2,400</MONEY> a month per pilot, said
<PERSON>John Mazor</PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION>ALPA</ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
   But the number of pilots paying those assessments to their
colleagues at <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> has decreased as the strike has worn on, <PERSON>Mazor</PERSON>
said in a telephone interview.
   ``That's typical for any (strike) assessment, for any labor
union,'' he said. ``It goes through a predictable cycle.''
   <ORGANIZATION>ALPA</ORGANIZATION> members are being balloted on whether to continue strike
benefits to their <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> colleagues, he said.
</TEXT>
