<HEAD>`Business as Usual' as Humbled Carrier Files for Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Continental-Analysis, PM-Continental-Chronology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY BENJAMINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bankruptcy court filing by <ORGANIZATION>Continental
Airlines</ORGANIZATION> leaves an empire built by ousted chairman <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> in
disarray, but the carrier says it will continue flying while it
tries to reorganize.
   The nation's fifth-largest airline blamed <MONEY>$2.2 billion</MONEY> in debt
and increased jet fuel costs due to the <LOCATION>Persian Gulf</LOCATION> crisis for
<DATE>Monday</DATE>'s decision to seek protection from creditors under Chapter
11 of federal bankruptcy laws.
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> said the move did not affect any of about 1,400
flights <DATE>Monday</DATE>. The airline serves 88 <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> cities and 55
international destinations with more than 300 planes. Its main hubs
are in <LOCATION>Newark</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.J.</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Denver</LOCATION>, and the airline is
building up a fourth hub in <LOCATION>Cleveland</LOCATION>.
   Management sought to reassure the airline's passengers and
37,000 employees the carrier planned to emerge from bankruptcy
court as an operating entity. The airline would fly its normal
schedule and honor contracts with travel agents and other airlines.
   ``We are confident that there will be no need for layoffs, pay
cuts or reductions in benefits,'' said <PERSON>Hollis Harris</PERSON>, chairman of
<ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines Holdings Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, the airline's parent, which
also filed for Chapter 11.
   The move, though, leaves in tatters an empire crafted by <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON>
from a hodgepodge of carriers including <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>People
Express</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Frontier</ORGANIZATION> and its huge debt is a legacy of its growth
during the <DATE>1980s</DATE>.
   Subsidiary <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> is struggling as it seeks to reorganize after
filing for bankruptcy protection in <DATE>1989</DATE>, <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> was ousted as
chairman earlier this year and his <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air Corp.</ORGANIZATION> was renamed.
   The trip to bankruptcy court was the second in seven years by
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, which filed in <DATE>1983</DATE> amid a bitter labor dispute with
the airline's union. Under Chapter 11, a company gets a reprieve
from debts while it figures out how to pay bills and tries to
reorganize as a healthy business.
   ``This is not a bankruptcy as was <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s in <DATE>1983</DATE> or
<ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s last year,'' <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s general counsel, <PERSON>Charles T.
Goolsbee</PERSON>, said. ``Remember, those airlines shut down. ... We are
doing none of that. This is absolutely a business-as-usual
program.''
   Some analysts said <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> may have a relatively smooth ride
through bankruptcy court, but recent shakeouts in the industry and
the uncertainty of the <LOCATION>Middle East</LOCATION> situation remain troubling.
   ``It's still a strong airline,'' said <PERSON>Raymond Neidl</PERSON>, an analyst
with <ORGANIZATION>Dillon Read &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION>, a Wall Street investment firm. ``They've
got good hubs and fairly cheap operating costs. They want to hold
onto most of these assets. In the long term, that could be good.''
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> said it had agreed to sell its <LOCATION>Seattle-Tacoma</LOCATION> to
<LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> route to <ORGANIZATION>American Airlines</ORGANIZATION> for <MONEY>$150 million</MONEY>, pending
bankruptcy court approval. The route sale is to be concluded at the
end of <DATE>1991</DATE>, but <MONEY>$140 million</MONEY> of the sale price is expected to be
advanced to <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> before the deal closes.
   As part of the sale, <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> withdrew its other
international routes from the market. Last month, <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> put
those up for sale instead of seeking bankruptcy protection.
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> has about <MONEY>$2.2 billion</MONEY> in outstanding debt, about
<MONEY>$1.7 billion</MONEY> of which is secured. It also has nearly <MONEY>$4 billion</MONEY> in
aircraft operating losses.
   <PERSON>Harris</PERSON> said the airline is spending an extra <MONEY>$70 million</MONEY> a month
on jet fuel because of a sharp rise since <ORGANIZATION>Iraq</ORGANIZATION> invaded <LOCATION>Kuwait</LOCATION> in
<DATE>August</DATE>. Prices more than doubled from about <MONEY>57 cents</MONEY> in <DATE>July</DATE> to
<MONEY>$1.28</MONEY> in mid-October before falling back in recent weeks.
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> now is paying <MONEY>$1.07</MONEY> per gallon. In addition, the
airline has increased passenger fares <PERCENT>15 percent</PERCENT> in recent months,
but spokesman <PERSON>Ned Walker</PERSON> said the hikes ``come nowhere near to
recovering our fuel costs.''
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> lost <MONEY>$88.3 million</MONEY> in the <DATE>third quarter</DATE> of this
year, compared to a loss of <MONEY>$158 million</MONEY> in <DATE>1989</DATE>. For the first
nine months, losses totaled <MONEY>$97 million</MONEY>, compared with <MONEY>$523 million</MONEY>
in the same period a year ago.
   Rising jet fuel costs have affected other airlines, but none had
filed for Chapter 11 before <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>.
   Earlier this <DATE>fall</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Pan Am Corp.</ORGANIZATION> announced it would sell five
prized <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> routes to <ORGANIZATION>UAL Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, the parent of <ORGANIZATION>United</ORGANIZATION>, in a <MONEY>$400
million</MONEY> deal. In addition, airlines have laid of thousands of
workers and some plan to cut capacities.
</TEXT>
