<HL> Texas Air Clears 10% SAS Stake, Discusses Sale of Shuttle to Trump </HL>
<AUTHOR> Bridget O'Brian and Roger Lowenstein (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> TEX EUROP </CO>
<IN> TNM AIR </IN>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, in major restructuring moves, agreed to let <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian Airlines System</ORGANIZATION> acquire a <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> equity stake and is holding talks to sell its <LOCATION>East Coast</LOCATION> air shuttle to developer <PERSON>Donald Trump</PERSON>. 

   The investment by <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> and the possible sale of the shuttle have been rumored for weeks. 
But the global scope of <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>'s joint operating arrangement with <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>, as well as the interest of <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> in the shuttle, had been closely guarded secrets. 

   The transaction with <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> establishes a wide-ranging combination of services between the two airlines, including the leasing of gates and landing rights to <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION>Newark</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.J.</LOCATION>, airport from <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION> unit. 

   In addition to the <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> equity stake -- which <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> will acquire in open-market purchases -- provisions of the agreement include ground service and joint-training arrangements, the payment of as much as <MONEY>$50 million</MONEY> in fees to <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> and its operating units and new arrangements permitting each airline to feed passengers into the route system of the other. 

   "We should work as vacuum cleaners to get people into the system" said <PERSON>Jan Carlzon</PERSON>, the expansion-minded chairman of <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>, a consortium of airlines partly owned by the governments of <LOCATION>Norway</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Denmark</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Sweden</LOCATION>. 

   The airlines called the agreement "the airline industry's first comprehensive global alliance among major international carriers." 
<PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON>, who built Houston-based <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> into the nation's largest airline company but who has begun shrinking it of late, added in an interview: "From where we stand, this is a sensible marriage. 
It gives tremendous strength and traffic support to <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>, and the same to <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>." 

   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> itself refused to comment on the negotiations to sell the <ORGANIZATION>East Coast</ORGANIZATION> shuttle to <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON>, but sources close to <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> confirmed the talks were under way. 
Sources say the price under discussion is in the neighborhood of <MONEY>$200 million</MONEY>. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Lorenzo</PERSON> declined to comment on any talks with <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON>. 
<PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> couldn't be reached and his attorney in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> declined to comment. 

   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>'s lucrative, three-city shuttle service, which is operated by <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, has been considered for purchase by, among others, <PERSON>Carl Icahn</PERSON>, the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> investor who control <ORGANIZATION>Trans World Airlines</ORGANIZATION>. 
The extent of <PERSON>Mr. Icahn</PERSON>'s interest couldn't be established. 

   <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>'s willingness to sell the operation has been clear for months. 
In a transaction that eventually was scuttled under legal pressure from hard-nosed unions at <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> proposed to transfer ownership of the operation from <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> to a newly created unit of <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> for <MONEY>$225 million</MONEY>. 
At the time, <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> proposed to sell a <PERCENT>20%</PERCENT> interest in the operation to private investors -- and <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> is among those who expressed an interest. 

   As further evidence to some inside the company that <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> is preparing the shuttle to be sold, shuttle planes have been refurbished, airport lounges have been renovated and flight attendants have been measured and outfitted for new uniforms that say simply, "Shuttle." 

   Real estate executives in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> say they have long suspected <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> of wanting to own an airline -- an asset that would be compatible with his extensive holdings in hotels and casinos. 
And the <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> shuttle has a high visibility in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> -- exactly the sort of asset that <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> covets. 

   A source close to the talks said <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON>, in the short term, would run the airline as is, and put in enough capital to upgrade service. 
"He thinks that with his name he can clean it up and get it to run on time," the source said. 

   However, another source familiar with <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> said that "his thought pattern all ties in with <LOCATION>Atlantic City</LOCATION>. 
The city is a fabulous play but the transportation into it is terrible. 
The biggest population centers for getting to <LOCATION>Atlantic City</LOCATION>," he added, are <LOCATION>Philadelphia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION>. 
The latter three are served by the <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> shuttle. 

   "They have a fabulous airport right there in <LOCATION>Atlantic City</LOCATION>," the source added, "but as of now they hardly use it." 

   <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> currently operates a regularly scheduled helicopter service (with four round trips daily) between <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Atlantic City</LOCATION>, mainly for gamblers and prize-fight fans. 
The helicopter service, which has a toll-free reservations number, is known as "Trump Air." 

   Sources said they expect the shuttle negotiations, which have been occurring since <DATE>last month</DATE>, to conclude in the next few weeks. 
However, a source close to the talks said the outcome of negotiations between two such "hard-nosed" figures as <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> and <PERSON>Mr. Lorenzo</PERSON> couldn't be guaranteed. 
"Can you imagine them negotiating with each other?" the source said. 

   However, <PERSON>Mr. Lorenzo</PERSON> and <PERSON>Mr. Carlzon</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> are an unlikely duo -- with the European airline chieftain making his reputation on high-quality service, harmonious relations with labor unions and strong earnings. 
<PERSON>Mr. Lorenzo</PERSON>, by contrast, has focused on cost-cutting to a degree that has led to phases of poor customer service, strife with unions and severe losses at both <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>. 

   But the stark difference is precisely what make the combination so compelling. 
For instance, <PERSON>Mr. Lorenzo</PERSON> said, <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>'s renowned <ORGANIZATION>Quality Training Institute</ORGANIZATION> will train all <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> employees. 
And <PERSON>Mr. Carlzon</PERSON> said he would call on <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>'s expertise with cost-cutting and competition as <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> prepares to face the deregulation of the European airline industry in three years. 

   "We must increase cost efficiency, we must have an information distribution system to reach the market, we must develop a traffic system and a hub system," <PERSON>Mr. Carlzon</PERSON> said. 
"We have a lot to learn in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> from the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>" 

   Specifically, <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> plans to introduce daily non-stop service from <LOCATION>Oslo</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Norway</LOCATION>, to <LOCATION>Newark</LOCATION> next <DATE>May</DATE> and move a flight that currently lands at <LOCATION>JFK airport</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Newark</LOCATION>. 
It will sublet three gates and passenger service facilities at <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s new <LOCATION>Newark</LOCATION> terminal. 
When <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> completes <MONEY>$100 million</MONEY> of proposed renovations at <LOCATION>JFK airport</LOCATION>, the two companies will discuss similar service to <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   The <MONEY>$50 million</MONEY> payment from <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> will be divided among the various <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> entities, with <MONEY>$25 million</MONEY> going to the parent corporation and <MONEY>$15 million</MONEY> to <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> for access to the <LOCATION>Newark</LOCATION> facility. 
The remaining <MONEY>$10 million</MONEY> will go to <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> for access to <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> facilities at <LOCATION>JFK Airport</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, when those facilities are completed. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Carlzon</PERSON> will become a member of the <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> board. 
As part of the agreement, <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> said it wouldn't fight <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> buying a stake in the company, which the European carrier said it would do within six months. 
The parties agreed that the stake wouldn't exceed <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> -- which is also the maximum interest a foreign carrier can hold in a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> carrier without <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> government approval. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Lorenzo</PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> originally wanted to buy the <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> stake directly from <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION>, but that he refused. 
"We didn't want to because we think our stock is too inexpensive and <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> doesn't have that kind of need for cash," he said. 

   In a statement, <PERSON>Mr. Lorenzo</PERSON> added: "Clearly, <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> thinks, as we do, that <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air</ORGANIZATION> shares are undervalued." 

   ---
   <PERSON>Amal Kumar Naj</PERSON> contributed to this article. 

