</CO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   STOCKHOLM -- Scandinavian Airlines System posted a big
pretax loss for 1990 and said that it expects to remain
unprofitable this year because of depressed airline markets
and continued restructuring costs.
   Jan Carlzon, chief executive officer, said that volatile
conditions in the airline industry made it practically
impossible to predict developments more than a few weeks
ahead.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> group, which besides the airline includes hotel
and charter travel units, is <PERCENT>50%</PERCENT>-owned by the governments of
<LOCATION>Denmark</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Norway</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Sweden</LOCATION>. It posted a <DATE>1990</DATE> pretax loss of
<MONEY>763 million Swedish kronor</MONEY> (<MONEY>$127.3 million</MONEY>) compared with
pretax profit of <MONEY>2.2 billion kronor</MONEY> (<MONEY>$367.1 million</MONEY>) a year
earlier. Operating profit last year fell <PERCENT>48%</PERCENT> to 649 million
kronor from <MONEY>1.24 billion kronor</MONEY> in <DATE>1989</DATE>.
   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> boosted operating profit with 700 million kronor from
the sale of used aircraft and other fixed assets during the
year. However, affiliated companies -- mainly the
<ORGANIZATION>Inter-Continental Hotels Group</ORGANIZATION> plus <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>'s flag carrier Lan
<LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> -- produced losses of 156 million kronor last year,
compared with <DATE>1989</DATE> profit of 83 million kronor. The remaining
<DATE>1990</DATE> operating profit was wiped out by <MONEY>1.7 billion kronor</MONEY> in
one-time charges.
   The nonrecurring items included writedowns for
shareholdings in affiliated companies -- such as a 500
million kronor decline in the market value of <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>'s <PERCENT>18.4%</PERCENT>
voting stake in troubled <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines Holdings</ORGANIZATION> of the
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Almost half of the one-time charges stemmed from a tough
cost-cutting program that is expected to eliminate 3,500 jobs
-- <PERCENT>17%</PERCENT> of the total payroll -- at the airline division by the
end of <DATE>1992</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Mr. Carlzon</PERSON> acknowledged that <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> almost certainly will
need to raise additional equity to complete the <MONEY>20 billion
kronor</MONEY> of aircraft purchases it plans during the coming
decade. However, the three government holders have frequently
balked at injecting as much equity as management wanted. And
they will be stung by the <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> board's decision to omit a
dividend for <DATE>1990</DATE>.
</TEXT>
