<HEAD>With AM-Lorenzo, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON> announced <DATE>Thursday</DATE> he would sell
his stake in <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airline Holdings Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, ending a stormy
tenure at the helm of what was once the nation's largest airline
company.
   Here is a rundown of highlights in his career:
   _<DATE>1963</DATE> _ Hired by <ORGANIZATION>Trans World Airlines</ORGANIZATION> as a financial analyst,
his first professional job.
   _<DATE>1965</DATE> _ Becomes manager of the financial analysis department at
<ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION>.
   _<DATE>1966</DATE> _ Forms an airline consulting firm with <ORGANIZATION>Harvard</ORGANIZATION> business
school classmate <PERSON>Robert Carney</PERSON> to explore business opportunities.
   _<DATE>1972</DATE> _ Becomes president of <ORGANIZATION>Texas International Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, after
a holding company he forms injects new capital into the ailing
airline.
   _1973-77 _ <ORGANIZATION>Rejuvenates Texas International</ORGANIZATION> using discounted
``peanut'' fares, more efficient routes and upgraded fleet.
   _<DATE>1980</DATE> _ Forms <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> Air to compete with <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> shuttle
service between <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
   _<DATE>1981</DATE> _ Wins control of <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION> over a rival
management-led buyout bid.
   _<DATE>1982</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>_ Merges Texas International and Continental</ORGANIZATION> under <ORGANIZATION>Texas
Air Corp</ORGANIZATION>.
   _<DATE>1983</DATE> _ Lays off <PERCENT>15 percent</PERCENT> of work force to bring down labor
costs; hires permanent replacements for striking machinists. Files
for bankruptcy protection to reorganize, voiding labor contracts.
Offers to rehire employees at half pay.
   _<DATE>1985</DATE> _ Loses a bid for <ORGANIZATION>Trans World Airlines</ORGANIZATION> to financier <PERSON>Carl
Icahn</PERSON>, and a bid for <ORGANIZATION>Frontier Airlines to People Express</ORGANIZATION>.
   _<DATE>1986</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>_ Acquires Eastern Airlines and People Express</ORGANIZATION> to form the
nation's biggest airline company.
   _<DATE>1987</DATE> _ Introduces discount Maxsaver fares and announces plans
to cut labor costs.
   _<DATE>1988</DATE> _ Undertakes a joint marketing operation with <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian
Airlines System</ORGANIZATION>, a leading European carrier.
   _<DATE>1989</DATE> _ <ORGANIZATION>Rejects Eastern</ORGANIZATION> union demands in contract negotiations.
Workers strike in <DATE>March</DATE>, <PERSON>Lorenzo</PERSON> puts the carrier under federal
bankruptcy protection and begins to sell many of <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s
important assets, including the <ORGANIZATION>Northeast</ORGANIZATION> shuttle. Parent company
loses <MONEY>$885.6 million</MONEY> for the year, an industry record.
   _<DATE>January-February 1990</DATE> _ Drastically reduces proposal for
repaying <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> creditors and faces increased problems in
bankruptcy court.
   _<DATE>April 1990</DATE> _ Loses control of <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION> to a court-appointed
trustee, <PERSON>Martin Shugrue</PERSON>. Renames <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air to Continental Airlines
Holdings Inc</ORGANIZATION>.
   _<DATE>Aug. 9, 1990</DATE> _ Announces resignation as chairman and chief
executive officer.
</TEXT>
