<LP>
   STOCKHOLM -- Jan Carlzon, the flashy chief executive of
Scandinavian Airlines System, prides himself on being a deft
communicator.
   But Mr. Carlzon has had trouble lately explaining signs of
a retrenchment under way at the half-state-owned airline of
Denmark, Norway and Sweden. While he and other company
officials stubbornly defended their dream of building a
global travel empire, assets acquired amid fanfare in a late
1980s buying binge have been quietly put up for sale.
                                                                                                       

   At a five-hour seminar for Scandinavian journalists here
this week, Mr. Carlzon finally set the record straight-sort
of. "When I described our global travel service company
concept in the past, it may have sounded like everything was
equally important," he explained. "That's not true. What
we're doing is streamlining operations so that everything
complements the airline, which is overwhelmingly the most
important element in the travel service idea."
   To that end, Mr. Carlzon remains bullish on the purchase
of a big minority stake in Continental Airlines Holdings,
parent of U.S. carrier Continental Airlines. SAS credits its
link with Continental's domestic traffic system for an 85%
surge in transit passengers in the past two years -- and an
improvement of 100 million Swedish kronor ($16.3 million) a
year in operating results from North Atlantic traffic.
   The U.S. routes still aren't profitable. "But I'm afraid
to even think where we'd be today had we not bought into
Continental," Mr. Carlzon said.
   However, Mr. Carlzon admitted he now regrets other
acquisitions -- from the 40% stake in Inter-Continental
Hotels group bought for $500 million to a 35% holding in
Chile's flag carrier Lan Chile. "We still want to reach out
to business travelers on the ground as well as in the air.
But we can do that by operating hotels, we realize we don't
need to own them," he added.
   As a result, both the Inter-Continental and Lan Chile
stakes are now on the block, Mr. Carlzon said, though he
insists he'll bide his time until he is offered the right
price. The SAS chief played down recent reports that SAS will
shed the Inter-Continental stake by November. "There have
been discussions but no negotiations with our partner. We
haven't reached any agreement and there isn't any time scale
agreed on yet," he declared.
   "We're also looking for ways to sell the Lan Chile stake.
But since the airline isn't losing money any more it isn't
urgent," Mr. Carlzon said.
   But slashing costs no doubt is the top priority. In
January, the airline unveiled a plan to cut annual costs by
three billion kronor, or roughly 20%, in part by eliminating
3,500 jobs by the end of next year. A majority of unions
representing SAS employees have agreed to negotiate
contracts, but Mr. Carlzon remains bogged down in a bitter
struggle with pilots and flight attendants that some analysts
fear may cause walkouts before a settlement.
   But Mr. Carlzon can't afford to waver yet. Even if air
travel perks up about 1993, as many industry analysts expect,
he warned that SAS will have to keep up pressure on costs to
survive fierce competition in deregulated European skies.
   Other than more draconian staff cuts, the only way to
control costs is through tighter cooperation with Swissair
and Austrian Airlines, partners since late 1989 in what Mr.
Carlzon dubbed the European Quality Alliance. The three
airlines recently agreed to intensify cooperation in
marketing, product development and integrating traffic
systems.
   The objective is to create a common image in markets
around Europe virtually as strong as if the airlines merged.
Yet such a merger, Mr. Carlzon stressed, can't be
contemplated today.
   That's partly a consequence of SAS's tangled ownership
structure; SAS and Swissair still haven't figured out how to
swap stakes of 5% to 10% in each other as outlined under a
September 1989 accord. Moreover, SAS executives worry that a
merger could threaten landing rights each of the three
airlines holds in the U.S. and various parts of Asia.
   Still, cooperation short of marriage could still yield
annual cost savings of up to 500 million kronor a year, Mr.
Carlzon said. And he disclosed that "there's now talk of
British Midland Airways becoming an active partner in the
alliance."
   The addition of British Midland, whose parent, Airlines of
Britain Holdings PLC, is 25%-owned by SAS, would give the
European Quality Alliance a hotly desired London hub. London,
together with Zurich, Vienna and Copenhagen, would comprise
the strongest hub network of any airline grouping in Europe,
Mr. Carlzon boasted.
   A spokesman for British Midland, however, said the carrier
"has announced no plans" to join the alliance and called such
reports "conjecture." Nonetheless, he added, the joint
marketing arrangements that British Midland has with SAS
would no doubt be affected by the Scandinavian carrier's
entrance into a deeper marketing alliance with Austrian and
Swissair.
   In addition, even the wisdom of tightening relations among
Quality Alliance members has met resistance. Founding member
Finnair pulled out of the alliance following the decision,
although it has pledged to maintain bilateral links with
remaining members.
   Finnair Executive Vice President Henrik Arle said the
alliance did not boost passenger traffic or market share for
his carrier, and added that Finnair was uncomfortable with
plans to turn over certain decision-making powers to a
committee. The European Quality Alliance "was not a failure,
but the achievements were not that remarkable," he said.
   ---
   Brian Coleman in Brussels contributed to this article.
