<HL>
   Continental
   Parent Posts
   Large Loss
   ----
   By Bridget O'Brian
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
03/22/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   CTA
</CO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   HOUSTON -- Continental Airlines Holdings Inc. reported an
unprecedented $2.25 billion fourth-quarter loss, the result
mainly of massive write-offs taken in an attempt to untangle
its complicated finances.
   The company, parent to Continental Airlines, blamed its
own bankruptcy filing, the liquidation of its Eastern
Airlines unit and the troubles besetting the entire airline
industry for the loss, which widened from a $362.8 million
loss in the year-earlier quarter. On a per-share basis, the
loss swelled to $52.37 from $9.17.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The write-downs, which account for more than <PERCENT>80%</PERCENT> of the
latest-quarter loss, reflect efforts by <ORGANIZATION>Continental Holdings</ORGANIZATION>
to put behind it the controversial and debt-laden legacy of
former chairman <PERSON>Frank Lorenzo</PERSON>, who borrowed huge sums to
assemble <ORGANIZATION>Continental Holdings</ORGANIZATION> -- then known as <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air
Corp.</ORGANIZATION> -- from four ailing carriers. <ORGANIZATION>Continental Holdings</ORGANIZATION> and
all its subsidiaries sought Chapter 11 protection in
<DATE>December</DATE>, squeezed for cash by their huge debt load and high
jet fuel prices.
   "Many of these write-offs could have been taken in the
future," said <PERSON>Hollis L. Harris</PERSON>, the airline's chairman and
president. "But reporting all of these expenses now will
allow the company to concentrate its efforts on successfully
emerging from Chapter 11 unencumbered by past events."
   To be sure, <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s losses weren't entirely the
result of one-time items. High fuel costs and a slowdown in
air travel combined to create a <DATE>fourth quarter</DATE> operating loss
at the holding company of <MONEY>$333.4 million</MONEY>. That loss was in
the same range as those posted by most airlines for the <DATE>last
quarter</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Mr. Hollis</PERSON> said he expected the nonrecurring, noncash
adjustments -- which totaled about <MONEY>$1.8 billion</MONEY> of the
quarterly loss -- to have no effect on continuing operations.
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s stock felt the impact, falling <MONEY>25 cents</MONEY> a
share to <MONEY>$3.25</MONEY> in <ORGANIZATION>American Stock Exchange</ORGANIZATION> trading.
   "Obviously, what they did was, they wiped the table
clean," said <PERSON>Timothy Pettee</PERSON>, a transportation analyst with
<ORGANIZATION>Alliance Capital Management</ORGANIZATION>. "The surviving balance sheet is
probably as ugly as you could get." <PERSON>Mr. Pettee</PERSON> estimates that
<ORGANIZATION>Continental Holdings</ORGANIZATION> currently has a negative book value of
<MONEY>$77</MONEY> a share as a result of the <DATE>fourth-quarter</DATE> results.
   Revenue declined <PERCENT>21%</PERCENT> to <MONEY>$1.38 billion</MONEY> in the <DATE>1990 fourth
quarter</DATE> from <MONEY>$1.73 billion</MONEY> a year earlier.
   For all of <DATE>1990</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> had a net loss of <MONEY>$2.34
billion</MONEY>, or <MONEY>$57.52</MONEY> a share, compared with a <DATE>1989</DATE> loss of
<MONEY>$885.6 million</MONEY> -- then a record -- or <MONEY>$22.71</MONEY> a share. Revenue
fell <PERCENT>6.8%</PERCENT> to <MONEY>$6.23 billion</MONEY> in <DATE>1990</DATE> from <MONEY>$6.68 billion</MONEY> in
<DATE>1989</DATE>.
   The <DATE>1989</DATE> figures include revenue from <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, a
unit operated by <ORGANIZATION>Continental Holdings</ORGANIZATION> until a bankruptcy
judge appointed a trustee to run it last <DATE>April</DATE>. Eastern
stopped flying in <DATE>January</DATE>, and <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> said it is writing
down <MONEY>$1.1 billion</MONEY> in connection with <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s liquidation.
   That includes more than <MONEY>$600 million</MONEY> <ORGANIZATION>Continental Holdings</ORGANIZATION>
is obliged to pay regarding <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s pension debt; about
<MONEY>$240 million</MONEY> for guarantees on <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s <PERCENT>11.36%</PERCENT> preferred
stock; and some other, smaller liabilities.
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental Holdings</ORGANIZATION> said it expects to take a deferred
credit relating to its investment in <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>, but won't do so
until it clears up potential litigation regarding the <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>
bankruptcy case. The credit could total as much as <MONEY>$1.1
billion</MONEY>, but given <ORGANIZATION>Eastern</ORGANIZATION>'s liquidation, <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION> isn't
likely to receive anything close to that amount.
   <ORGANIZATION>Continental Holdings</ORGANIZATION> also said it was writing down <MONEY>$439.6
million</MONEY>, primarily in "good will" created as a result of its
various mergers and acquisitions in <DATE>1986</DATE> and <DATE>1987</DATE>. That total
also includes various deferred expenses and debt discounts.
   The company also wrote off <MONEY>$270 million</MONEY> for impairment of
assets, most of which reflects the declining value of older,
noisier aircraft that generally will be banned by decade's
end. About <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> of the <MONEY>$270 million</MONEY> write-down covers
<ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION>Denver</LOCATION> terminal and maintenance hangar, which
it will have to give up in <DATE>1993</DATE> when it moves to new quarters
at the <LOCATION>Denver</LOCATION> airport currently under construction.
   Even after the one-time charges are accounted for, the
company's chief subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION>, had hefty
losses of its own. The airline blamed those losses on jet
fuel expenses, which added <MONEY>$201 million</MONEY> to operating costs in
the third and fourth quarters. As a result, <ORGANIZATION>Continental
Airlines</ORGANIZATION> posted a <DATE>fourth-quarter</DATE> operating loss of <MONEY>$299.6
million</MONEY> on revenue of <MONEY>$1.3 billion</MONEY>. In the <DATE>year-earlier
quarter</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION> had an operating loss of only
<MONEY>$8 million</MONEY> on revenue of <MONEY>$1.2 billion</MONEY>.
</TEXT>
