<HL> SAS, Swissair Set Agreement to Swap
@  Stakes in New Travel-Service Alliance
@  ----
@  By Susan Carey
@  Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal </HL>
<DD> 09/29/89 </DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J) </SO>
<CO> K.SAI Z.SR EUROP R.AAI </CO>
<IN> TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AIRLINES (AIR)
REAL ESTATE, REITS, LAND DEVELOPMENT (REL) </IN>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Scandinavian Airlines System</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> announced plans to swap stakes of <PERCENT>5%</PERCENT> to <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> in each other under a broad air-traffic and travel-services alliance. 

   The two carriers said the planned partnership will give them sufficient critical mass to be among five surviving Europe-based intercontinental carriers in a deregulated air industry of the <DATE>1990s</DATE>. 
They said planned coordination of their traffic-systems, marketing and other functions would save about <MONEY>200 million Swedish kronor</MONEY> (<MONEY>$31 million</MONEY>) a year. 
The gains are expected to multiply as cooperation evolves -- with resulting profits shared equally. 

   The plan, which was announced simultaneously in <LOCATION>Zurich</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Switzerland</LOCATION>, and <LOCATION>Stockholm</LOCATION>, also is intended to include areas such as catering, hotels, fleet planning and product development. 
But most of the details remain to be worked out. 

   SAS Chief Executive Officer <PERSON>Jan Carlzon</PERSON> said that if the <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> alliance develops according to plan, the level of cross-ownership will increase in the future. 
<ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> said representation on each other's boards may occur. 
<PERSON>Mr. Carlzon</PERSON> said existing partners such as <ORGANIZATION>Airlines of Britain PLC</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Austrian Airlines</ORGANIZATION> could be included in the coordinated air-traffic scheme. 
In addition, he proposed that <ORGANIZATION>Finnair</ORGANIZATION> join the group. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Carlzon</PERSON> called <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> "an ideal partner" with a similar strategy focused on business travelers and high-quality service. 
He said <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> boasts the extensive long-haul network in <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Middle East</LOCATION>, places where <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> is weak. 

   <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> said the two airlines initially will increase seat capacity on their flights linking <LOCATION>Zurich</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Geneva</LOCATION> with the three Nordic capitals. 
Travelers from <LOCATION>Scandinavia</LOCATION> would then be able to fly to <LOCATION>Switzerland</LOCATION> and connect onto <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> flights to, say, <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> or <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>, while passengers from central <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> could fly to <LOCATION>Copenhagen</LOCATION> to connect to <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> flights to <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>. 
The two airlines could operate joint flights, split up frequencies by time or day or simply harmonize their existing schedules in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> said. 

   But the <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> chief acknowledged that <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION>Zurich</LOCATION> hub is less attractive than <LOCATION>Brussels</LOCATION> or other European capitals which <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> earlier considered as possible gateways for intercontinental routes. 
A couple of years ago, <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> tried very hard to arrange a merger with <ORGANIZATION>Sabena</ORGANIZATION>. 
Further, since <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> have different partners in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, the new alliance probably won't have much impact on <LOCATION>North Atlantic</LOCATION> traffic, <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> officials said. 

   SAS last year bought <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> of <ORGANIZATION>Texas Air Corp.</ORGANIZATION> as a way of cementing a marketing alliance with the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> concern's <ORGANIZATION>Continental Airlines</ORGANIZATION> unit. 
Recently, <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> had been talking to <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> Air about buying more or all of <ORGANIZATION>Continental</ORGANIZATION>, with <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> partners. 
<ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, in <DATE>March</DATE> signed a marketing deal with <ORGANIZATION>Delta Air Lines</ORGANIZATION>. 
Four months later, the two swapped <PERCENT>5%</PERCENT> stakes, <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> paying about <MONEY>$193 million</MONEY> and <ORGANIZATION>Delta</ORGANIZATION> about <MONEY>$77 million</MONEY>. 

   <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON>Armin Baltensweiler</PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION>Delta</ORGANIZATION> tie-up gave his company extra incentive to reach an agreement with <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>. 
Between <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Delta</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> is closer to its goal of safeguarding its long-term competitiveness. 

   The agreement, approved by <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION>'s board <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> and <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> directors yesterday, calls for an exchange of shares, but the exact size of the respective shareholdings will be the subject of further negotiations. 
So will the composition of the joint executive board that will steer the partnership. 

   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> intend to complete the share swap by the <DATE>summer</DATE>. 
But executives admit they haven't agreed on a method of valuation. 
<ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION>'s complex ownership is another potential pitfall. 
<LOCATION>Scandinavia</LOCATION>'s airline is half-owned by the Danish, Norwegian and Swedish governments with the remaining <PERCENT>50%</PERCENT> split among publicly traded holding companies in each of the three Nordic countries. 
<ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> is <PERCENT>23%</PERCENT> owned by federal and cantonal authorities. 

   <ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> also said they intend to integrate their hotels under a global travel-service system. 
<ORGANIZATION>SAS</ORGANIZATION> owns 23 hotels directly and holds interests in 105 more through its <PERCENT>40%</PERCENT> stake in <ORGANIZATION>Intercontinental Hotel Corp.</ORGANIZATION> acquired earlier this year. 

</TEXT>
